ning, placenames and personal names, and the development of Scots overseas. Each chapter gives a brief overview of the topic, and provides case studies to illustrate avenues of exploration for those beginning to develop research techniques. The book is designed as an accessible introduction to key issues and methods of investigation for undergraduate students interested in the way language has developed in Scotland.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aScots languagexResearch. 0aScots language. 4aLanguage & Linguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aCorbett, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHough, Carole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacafee, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcClure, J. Derrick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMcClure, J. Derrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeurman-Solin, Anneli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontgomery, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScott, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Jeremy J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStuart-Smith, Jane, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aStuart-Smith, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147442159140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474421591423Coveruhttps: